<p>factoredExp = $factoredExp</p>
<p>factor1= $factor1</p>
<p>factor2= $factor2</p> -->
<!--testing-->



<problem>

  
<p>Factor 
  <me>$fullExprExp{simplify}</me>
</p>
  <p><m>$fullExprExp{simplify} = </m><mathInput name="userFactored"/> 
    <answer name="ans9">
      <award>
        <when>
          <hasSameFactoring>$userFactored $factoredExp</hasSameFactoring>
        </when>
      </award>
      <award name="signError" credit="0">
        <when>
          $userFactored = $signErrorAns1
          or
          $userFactored = $signErrorAns2
        </when>
      </award>
      <award name="noFactoring" credit="0">
        <when>
          $userFactored = $factoredExp{expand}
        </when>
      </award>
    </answer></p>

<!--*********************************************
            Feedbacks
**********************************************-->

   <feedback condition="$signError">
    <p>It looks like you have a sign error somewhere.</p>
  <p><em>How to check</em>: FOIL out your factored answer to see if it matches your original, expanded quadratic expression.</p></feedback>

  <feedback condition="$noFactoring">
  <p>To factor the quadratic expression <m>($factoredExp{expand})</m>, means to split it into two factors, if possible. Generally, this means to separate it into two binomial terms, or a monomial term and a binomial term. Here are two simple examples:</p>
<ul>
  <li><m>x^2 + 4x - 5 = (x - 1)(x + 5)</m></li>
  <li><m>2x^2 + 4x = 2x(x + 2)</m></li>
</ul>
  
<p><em>How to check</em>: It is ok to use a bit of trial and error when factoring. Choose a possible factoring, and then FOIL it out to see if it matches your original, expanded quadratic expression.</p>
  </feedback>




