**********************************************-->
<hint name="helpSection"><title>Worked Example</title>
    <p>First, check to see if the expression has a greatest common factor. In this case, we do not have a GCF, so we proceed to factor the trinomial.</p>
<p>For a trinomial with an <m>x^2</m> coefficient of <m>1</m>, it is sufficient to ask "what two factors of the constant term add up to the coefficient on the <m>x</m> term?" </p>
<p>Notice that in this problem, the coefficient on the <m>x</m> term is negative, but the constant term is positive. From this, we can infer that the factors of the constant term will be two negative numbers. Here is a simple worked example:</p>
        <me>\text{Factor}\;\;x^2 - 20x +100</me>
  We need two factors of <m>100</m> that add up to <m>-20</m>. We only need to considering negative factors. The negative factor pairs of <m>100</m> are
    <md>
      <mrow>(-1\;\; \amp\text{and}\;\; -100)</mrow>
      <mrow>(-2\;\; \amp\text{and}\;\; -50)</mrow>
      <mrow>(-4\;\; \amp\text{and}\;\; -25)</mrow>
      <mrow>(-5\;\; \amp\text{and}\;\; -20)</mrow>
      <mrow>(-10\;\; \amp\text{and}\;\; -10)</mrow>
      </md> 
  The negative factor pair that adds up to <m>-20</m> is <m>(-10</m> and <m>-10)</m>. Therefore, we have
  <me>x^2 - 20x + 100 = (x - 10)(x - 10)\;\;\text{or}\;\;(x-10)^2</me>
<p><em>How to check</em>: Always FOIL it out to see if it matches your original expression.</p>


